    rationale: "JVP is calculated by adding 5 cm to the measured height of the venous pulsation above the sternal angle, to account for the anatomical distance from the sternal angle to the right atrium. Here: 4 cm + 5 cm = 9 cm H2O. Normal JVP is <8\u20139 cm H2O, so this value is at the upper limit of normal \u2014 not clearly elevated. A value >9 cm H2O would be considered elevated. The 5 cm correction is essential; omitting it would underestimate JVP. Any visible pulsation above the clavicle is not inherently abnormal without applying this correction.",
