    rationale: "In LV failure, elevated LVEDP backs up into the pulmonary veins and capillaries, raising pulmonary venous and arterial pressure. This increases RV afterload. Over time, the RV fails under this increased pressure, raising right atrial pressure \u2014 which is reflected as elevated JVP. This is the classic sequence of left-to-right heart failure propagation. Pressure is not directly transmitted through the mitral valve to the jugular veins \u2014 the pulmonary circulation is the intermediary. Renal vasoconstriction causes sodium retention and volume overload, which contributes indirectly. RAAS does not directly constrict jugular veins.",
